40
00:03:17,447 --> 00:03:25,852
So this approach to economics that I'm part of, it's called Modern Monetary Theory or MMT for short.

41
00:03:26,452 --> 00:03:32,116
You've probably seen it all over the news in the last year or so, at least on the national stage.

42
00:03:33,056 --> 00:03:40,601
It's a very simple set of observations to describe how the system currently works.

43
00:03:41,361 --> 00:03:42,842
And it's trying to highlight

44
00:03:43,634 --> 00:03:48,396
the mechanics of the existing ways we finance federal spending.

45
00:03:49,036 --> 00:03:53,378
And it's trying to highlight some of the key limitations and some of the key obstacles.

46
00:03:53,859 --> 00:04:07,625
And it just happens to be an approach that goes completely against the mainstream understanding of what federal spending supposed to be and what the real constraints are supposed to be.

47
00:04:07,705 --> 00:04:10,586
So let me put it this way, a couple of observations.

48
00:04:10,666 --> 00:04:13,047
Number one, the federal government

49
00:04:13,868 --> 00:04:26,795
is very different from a financial standpoint, very different from state and local municipal governments, is very different than you and I. So you and I have to work hard, earn an income first, then we spend it.

50
00:04:27,415 --> 00:04:33,598
You and I can also borrow if we want to spend beyond our income, buy a big house or buy a new car or whatever.

51
00:04:33,638 --> 00:04:38,781
But once we borrow, we have a debt that must be paid at some point in the future.

52
00:04:39,497 --> 00:04:48,041
And the only way to pay that debt is either by earning more income somehow or spending less on other things so we can pay the bills.

53
00:04:48,482 --> 00:04:49,622
That's the only way to do it.

54
00:04:50,143 --> 00:04:56,306
Your local municipalities, your states, your cities also function the same way you and I function.

55
00:04:56,806 --> 00:04:59,968
They collect tax revenues from their residents.

56
00:05:00,728 --> 00:05:08,252
They use those tax revenues to spend on schools and housing and whatever programs the city or municipalities are spending on.

57
00:05:09,011 --> 00:05:09,471
And that's it.

58
00:05:09,511 --> 00:05:10,992
They're limited by tax revenues.

59
00:05:11,272 --> 00:05:16,053
They can borrow to build a new school, to build a new stadium for the city or whatever.

60
00:05:16,493 --> 00:05:27,536
But now the city has debt or the state has debt that must be paid for at some point in the future, maybe the next 20 years or so, by raising more tax revenues.

61
00:05:27,576 --> 00:05:29,116
That's why we have school levies.

62
00:05:29,256 --> 00:05:29,476
Right.

63
00:05:29,536 --> 00:05:35,538
That's why city taxes and state taxes go up to pay for those big expenditures.

64
00:05:35,917 --> 00:05:40,722
So that's the meaning of debt for you and I, for cities, for municipalities.

65
00:05:41,282 --> 00:05:43,784
And it's so ingrained in us, right?

66
00:05:43,824 --> 00:05:49,550
Because we live with it day to day and we have this fear of what might happen if we go into debt.

67
00:05:49,570 --> 00:05:51,051
We've known people have gone into debt.

68
00:05:52,092 --> 00:05:56,596
It's a thing that's very difficult for us to think differently.

69
00:05:57,177 --> 00:05:57,617
Exactly.

70
00:05:57,657 --> 00:05:59,299
So we learn to live within our means.

71
00:06:00,122 --> 00:06:07,131
as families as as companies as nonprofit organizations where you have to raise revenues before you spend them right.

72
00:06:07,632 --> 00:06:10,055
You don't have unlimited borrowing capacity.

73
00:06:10,496 --> 00:06:13,620
And cities and municipalities also learn to live within their means.

74
00:06:14,241 --> 00:06:18,066
If the public is demanding this big thing this ambitious thing

75
00:06:18,868 --> 00:06:21,912
The city or the state will say, well, too bad.

76
00:06:21,972 --> 00:06:22,913
We just can't afford it.

77
00:06:23,533 --> 00:06:28,478
We have to settle for a smaller version of the thing that you're asking for.

78
00:06:28,899 --> 00:06:37,328
But at the federal level, there is a very different mechanism for running public finances that is very different.

79
00:06:37,798 --> 00:06:40,200
from the rest of us users of the dollar.

80
00:06:40,540 --> 00:06:44,184
Think of the federal government as the issuer of the dollar.

81
00:06:44,264 --> 00:06:48,547
It's the only entity that can legally print the currency to begin with.

82
00:06:49,048 --> 00:06:52,711
But it's also, you know, functioning in a completely different way.

83
00:06:53,271 --> 00:07:05,502
And I'll highlight a few historical examples that people will connect to, to understand that the federal government is not limited the same way your state or municipality or you and I are limited.

84
00:07:05,972 --> 00:07:07,853
Some historical examples, some very recent.

85
00:07:07,873 --> 00:07:09,534
I'm talking about the CARES Act, for example.

86
00:07:10,094 --> 00:07:16,938
So when the CARES Act was being introduced in Washington, D.C.

87
00:07:16,998 --> 00:07:22,401
six months ago, if you go back just a couple of weeks before that, everybody in D.C.

88
00:07:22,421 --> 00:07:25,023
was convinced there was no money for a Green New Deal.

89
00:07:25,303 --> 00:07:26,884
There is no money for Medicare for All.

90
00:07:26,924 --> 00:07:29,165
There's no money for broadband infrastructure.

91
00:07:30,315 --> 00:07:34,197
Everybody was convinced, Democrats, Republicans, the general public that we're broke.

92
00:07:34,337 --> 00:07:39,619
You know, there's no way we can spend trillions of dollars on these ambitious transformative programs.

93
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:46,583
And we were told just to settle for either nothing or maybe hopefully a little bit, you know, and over time we'll deal with it.

94
00:07:47,283 --> 00:07:54,146
But then all of a sudden the pandemic hits and we realize that we need to intervene on a massive scale.

95
00:07:55,329 --> 00:07:57,110
to provide relief for the U.S.

96
00:07:58,532 --> 00:08:00,233
consumers and businesses and so on.

97
00:08:00,633 --> 00:08:03,997
So all of a sudden, 535 people in D.C.

98
00:08:04,397 --> 00:08:08,261
get together and they vote to approve trillions of dollars worth of spending.

99
00:08:09,081 --> 00:08:16,048
And they did it without telling us who they borrowed from, which they didn't borrow from anybody, or who they taxed.

100
00:08:17,058 --> 00:08:26,728
On top of it, the president and the secretary of Treasury came out during that same week and said, by the way, April 15th is right around the corner.

101
00:08:27,128 --> 00:08:28,690
Don't worry about paying your taxes.

102
00:08:28,850 --> 00:08:30,311
We don't need your taxes.

103
00:08:30,571 --> 00:08:32,894
We'll postpone that to July 15th or whatever.

104
00:08:33,314 --> 00:08:34,896
So we didn't tax anybody.

105
00:08:35,016 --> 00:08:36,237
We didn't borrow from anybody.

106
00:08:36,617 --> 00:08:40,241
And the taxes that were due the following month, we told you we don't actually need it.

107
00:08:41,056 --> 00:08:43,518
And that's how the federal government always spends.

108
00:08:43,578 --> 00:08:48,843
The federal government doesn't need tax revenues or borrowing in order to spend.

109
00:08:49,203 --> 00:08:55,068
Now, taxing and borrowing are still important, but they're not the thing we use to finance spending.

110
00:08:55,629 --> 00:08:58,811
I'll give you even a better example, which is World War II.

111
00:08:59,232 --> 00:09:03,756
World War II came right after the Great Depression, the most miserable time in U.S.

112
00:09:03,796 --> 00:09:04,156
history.

113
00:09:04,593 --> 00:09:09,556
There was no money to be taxed in the economy, and there was no money to be borrowed, right?

114
00:09:09,576 --> 00:09:12,798
So that's like the very definition of broke, right?

115
00:09:13,039 --> 00:09:14,199
The system was broke.

116
00:09:14,700 --> 00:09:22,024
And all of a sudden, World War II is staring at us as a US economy.

117
00:09:22,885 --> 00:09:28,529
And we have to spend a massive amount of money to build for the war effort and to win the war.

118
00:09:29,109 --> 00:09:33,452
Now, can you imagine if we used our local city municipal budget thinking,

119
00:09:34,162 --> 00:09:37,825
during World War II and said, well, listen, this thing is really expensive.

120
00:09:37,905 --> 00:09:38,886
We can't afford it.

121
00:09:40,087 --> 00:09:43,169
We can only afford a small, mini portion of the war.

122
00:09:43,209 --> 00:09:47,092
So how about we send 5,000 troops to Germany and see if we can scare them away?

123
00:09:47,813 --> 00:09:49,534
Do the incremental solution, right?

124
00:09:49,554 --> 00:09:50,755
You can't do that, obviously.

125
00:09:51,116 --> 00:09:55,899
So how did we pay for World War II without taxing anybody, without borrowing for anybody?

126
00:09:56,280 --> 00:09:58,862
Well, the government did it the same way they spend on any program.

127
00:10:00,983 --> 00:10:03,024
You know, not just those programs, not just the CARES Act.

128
00:10:03,204 --> 00:10:05,765
This is how the government always spends.

129
00:10:05,785 --> 00:10:08,367
535 people vote, approve the spending.

130
00:10:08,667 --> 00:10:10,348
The spending is done.

131
00:10:10,708 --> 00:10:12,369
It enters into the economy.

132
00:10:12,913 --> 00:10:20,780
The part that we should be concerned about, and we were very concerned about during World War II, is what will be the effect of this additional spending?

133
00:10:21,140 --> 00:10:24,323
We know that the government can spend as long as it's approved by Congress.

134
00:10:24,503 --> 00:10:25,384
It's the law.

135
00:10:25,564 --> 00:10:27,306
The Congress has the power of the purse.

136
00:10:27,826 --> 00:10:35,133
The thing that Congress should always be concerned about, and we were very concerned about during World War II, was the risk of inflation.

137
00:10:35,593 --> 00:10:37,675
If we flood the system with

138
00:10:38,877 --> 00:10:47,442
billions of dollars worth of decent wages for people who are building the airplanes and the tanks and the military equipment, what will they do with that money?

139
00:10:47,782 --> 00:10:48,883
Well, it's a free country.

140
00:10:48,943 --> 00:10:54,586
They're gonna go out and wanna buy a house or wanna buy a car or wanna go on vacation, whatever it is, right?

141
00:10:54,646 --> 00:10:55,307
It's a free country.

142
00:10:55,347 --> 00:10:56,687
That's freedom, that's democracy.

143
00:10:57,208 --> 00:10:58,408
Except there was a problem.

144
00:10:59,049 --> 00:11:04,332
We had the vast majority of the working people of this country

145
00:11:04,995 --> 00:11:12,258
busy producing military equipment and not enough people producing cars or homes or any of the consumer goods.

146
00:11:12,778 --> 00:11:24,702
So we were going to be facing a situation where lots of people building airplanes have cash and they want to go out on a shopping spree and now they're going to bid up the price of homes and cars and consumer goods and cause inflation.

147
00:11:25,122 --> 00:11:28,383
So what did we do to prevent that scenario from happening?

148
00:11:29,317 --> 00:11:34,742
We leveraged the patriotic mood of the nation and said, here's what you're going to do.

149
00:11:35,162 --> 00:11:37,564
You're going to buy this freedom bond from the U.S.

150
00:11:37,604 --> 00:11:38,025
Treasury.

151
00:11:38,245 --> 00:11:45,031
They call them freedom bonds and war bonds, which means you're going to give me, say, $10,000 of your hard earned income.

152
00:11:45,551 --> 00:11:48,594
You're going to save it by buying this freedom bond.

153
00:11:48,714 --> 00:11:49,594
And we, the U.S.

154
00:11:49,655 --> 00:11:55,920
Treasury, promise to pay you back in 10 years or 15 years or whatever the duration is, plus interest.

155
00:11:56,395 --> 00:12:02,278
which means after the war, we'll give you your money back plus interest, and then you can go out on a shopping spree.

156
00:12:02,658 --> 00:12:03,979
And that was the post-war boom.

157
00:12:04,499 --> 00:12:10,722
But notice, the sale of those freedom bonds and treasury bonds didn't happen before World War II.

158
00:12:11,103 --> 00:12:13,624
It wasn't to finance World War II, like most people think.

159
00:12:13,944 --> 00:12:19,327
It happened during World War II, as the money was already spent into existence.

160
00:12:19,787 --> 00:12:23,710
We found a way to pull it back out in a less coercive way.

161
00:12:24,130 --> 00:12:25,291
So we could have taxed it away.

162
00:12:25,671 --> 00:12:27,192
We could have coercively taken the money.

163
00:12:27,572 --> 00:12:29,734
But of course, why would you want to do that?

164
00:12:29,894 --> 00:12:32,336
You tax the upper income, you tax for other reasons.

165
00:12:32,796 --> 00:12:34,577
But the sale of those U.S.

166
00:12:34,637 --> 00:12:39,340
Treasury bonds, which we call borrowing, I mean, why would the government need to borrow its own money?

167
00:12:39,620 --> 00:12:40,561
That's kind of a silly thing.

168
00:12:41,355 --> 00:12:46,158
You and I call it borrowing, but from the federal government perspective, it's not for the purpose of borrowing.

169
00:12:46,558 --> 00:12:52,742
At the time it was for the purpose of taming the risk of inflation, postponing consumption until after the war.

170
00:12:53,062 --> 00:13:00,086
There are other reasons also for selling government bonds, stabilizing interest rates and so on, which we can get into, but it gets more technical.

171
00:13:00,706 --> 00:13:02,307
Can I just pause you for a second?

172
00:13:02,387 --> 00:13:03,448
Yeah, of course.

173
00:13:03,968 --> 00:13:05,909
So I want to go back a little bit, right?

174
00:13:06,430 --> 00:13:08,651
Because I think when we use this term,

175
00:13:09,051 --> 00:13:10,953
spending, like the government is spending.

176
00:13:10,973 --> 00:13:26,768
I think it's very hard for us, you know, as people who spend money, who earn money, spend money, borrow money, when we talk about the federal government as spending money and borrowing money, I think it's hard for people to understand how it's different for the federal government.

177
00:13:27,128 --> 00:13:34,375
So when the federal government, let me just ask this question, when the federal government spends money,

178
00:13:34,968 --> 00:13:41,131
and you say spend into existence, like they're actually creating more dollars, right?

179
00:13:41,151 --> 00:13:43,172
So they're increasing the money supply, right?

180
00:13:43,292 --> 00:13:45,273
So it's not like they're spending.

181
00:13:45,333 --> 00:13:52,336
They're just creating more dollars and giving those new dollars to people or companies.

182
00:13:52,476 --> 00:13:53,216
Is that accurate?

183
00:13:53,817 --> 00:13:54,757
Yeah, absolutely.

184
00:13:54,857 --> 00:13:56,078
Think of federal spending.

185
00:13:56,318 --> 00:14:00,900
Every time the federal government spends, it's always spending new money into the economy.

186
00:14:01,422 --> 00:14:01,722
Right.

187
00:14:01,983 --> 00:14:05,305
Whether it's going to corporations or individuals or whatever, it's always new money.

188
00:14:05,706 --> 00:14:11,171
Every time the government taxes money out of the system, think of it as dollars being destroyed.

189
00:14:11,271 --> 00:14:13,052
It's taxed out of existence.

190
00:14:13,593 --> 00:14:13,813
But.

191
00:14:14,442 --> 00:14:18,803
when your local tax authority is taxing, it's not taxing and destroying those dollars.

192
00:14:19,103 --> 00:14:24,004
They're taxing in order to spend because they're like you and I. They earn the dollars and they have to spend them.

193
00:14:24,284 --> 00:14:30,785
The federal government doesn't need to borrow from you or from me in order to start a war, right?

194
00:14:30,845 --> 00:14:32,766
Congress decides when they want to start a war.

195
00:14:32,826 --> 00:14:35,546
Congress decides when they want to pay for the CARES Act.

196
00:14:35,606 --> 00:14:37,927
Congress decides when they want to pass a tax cut.

197
00:14:38,472 --> 00:14:48,075
It has nothing to do with my permission, me giving them permission, other than voting for different politicians, depending on their platform.

198
00:14:48,496 --> 00:14:53,477
But we don't decide what tax dollars are going to do.

199
00:14:53,537 --> 00:14:57,599
Congress always approves the spending, case in point, every time there is a war.

200
00:15:02,296 --> 00:15:03,579
You know, where does the money come from?

201
00:15:03,599 --> 00:15:05,021
It's always a deficit.

202
00:15:05,282 --> 00:15:06,865
There doesn't have to be a war either.

203
00:15:06,925 --> 00:15:10,471
We can just increase the military budget for no reason at all.

204
00:15:11,154 --> 00:15:19,037
And that money is created by the federal government because the federal government is the only entity in the world that can create dollars.

205
00:15:19,617 --> 00:15:19,777
Right.

206
00:15:20,217 --> 00:15:27,680
So here's a takeaway point from this understanding the difference between us, the users of the dollar versus the federal government.

207
00:15:28,200 --> 00:15:30,701
Every time I have a deficit, it's a problem.

208
00:15:30,981 --> 00:15:33,522
Every time you have a deficit with your bank, it's a problem.

209
00:15:33,842 --> 00:15:36,483
When your city has a deficit, they have to cut their spending.

210
00:15:36,833 --> 00:15:39,154
When the state has a deficit, they have to cut their spending.

211
00:15:39,754 --> 00:15:42,375
That's the prudent, reasonable thing to do, right?

212
00:15:42,435 --> 00:15:45,216
When businesses have a deficit, they have to worry about it.

213
00:15:45,577 --> 00:15:56,041
But when the federal government has a deficit, it simply means that it spent more dollars into the economy than what it has taxed out of the system.

214
00:15:56,461 --> 00:16:03,064
And that means that it created more dollars in the economy than it destroyed, right?

215
00:16:03,104 --> 00:16:05,825
So it simply increased the amount of money in the economy.

216
00:16:06,333 --> 00:16:10,556
So then the deficit, let's say it's a trillion dollar deficit to keep the numbers simple.

217
00:16:10,917 --> 00:16:18,663
