Think of energy companies.

426
00:33:17,785 --> 00:33:19,105
Think of real estate companies.

427
00:33:19,145 --> 00:33:20,126
Why do they raise prices?

428
00:33:20,446 --> 00:33:22,627
Because they can, because they dominate the market.

429
00:33:22,987 --> 00:33:24,928
So that kind of inflation risk

430
00:33:25,533 --> 00:33:27,796
It's not going to go away by spending less.

431
00:33:28,476 --> 00:33:33,462
It only goes away if you tax and regulate that market power out of existence.

432
00:33:33,883 --> 00:33:37,947
In other words you make those markets more democratic more competitive.

433
00:33:38,568 --> 00:33:44,555
And if you do that if we're successful at doing that then all of a sudden we've just increased our spending capacity.

434
00:33:45,263 --> 00:33:51,386
quite a lot, which means we can now afford more of an ambitious Green New Deal or healthcare program.

435
00:33:51,767 --> 00:34:12,478
But if we can't, if we leave the risk of inflation where it is, by not building more capacity, by not training more people, and by not taxing and regulating that market power, then we keep that fiscal spending space very limited and say, oh, it's too bad, we can't afford it because big pharma didn't let us and the super PACs didn't let us.

436
00:34:13,211 --> 00:34:18,074
My final point here is that it's those 535 people we elect in D.C.

437
00:34:18,134 --> 00:34:21,897
whose responsibility is to tax and regulate that market power.

438
00:34:22,637 --> 00:34:25,720
